South African Equities: Absa, BHP, Coronation, Sasol, Vodacom

-- B y   L a u r e n   v a n   d e r   W e s t h u i z e n   a n d   R e n e e   B o n o r c h i s
-- 
2011-04-28T15:43:55Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-28/south-african-stocks-fall-snapping-four-day-climb-absa-gold-one-decline.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
snapped a four-day advance, losing 8.2, or less than 0.1
percent, to 32,659.95 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Absa Group Ltd. (ASA)  ,  South Africa ’s largest retail
bank, dropped for the first day in three, slumping 3.35 rand, or
2.4 percent, to 135.15 rand. Absa’s profit before tax decreased
19 percent to 135 million pounds ($225 million), according to a
statement by its parent company Barclays Plc.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s biggest mining
company, slumped for the second day, losing 3.73 rand, or 1.3
percent, to 277.62 rand. Copper imports into China, the largest
user, may decline this month compared with a year ago, falling
for a third month, said Xiao Jing, an analyst at Beijing Capital
Futures Co.  Coronation Fund Managers Ltd. (CML)  , which said it had
assets under management of about $33.8 billion as of Dec. 30,
rose 9 cents, or 0.5 percent, to 18.84 rand. The company said
fiscal first-half earnings per share rose between 30 percent and
40 percent. Coronation will release a full earnings report on
May 17.  Gold One International Ltd. (GDO)  , a miner of the
precious metal, snapped three days of gains, losing 15 cents, or
4.2 percent, to 3.45 rand. The company agreed to acquire Rand
Uranium Ltd. for $250 million.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, fell for the first time in five trading
sessions, losing 7.25 rand, or 1.9 percent, to 378.20 rand. A
maintenance shutdown is planned at its synthetic fuels
operations from Aug. 26 to Sept. 12, and a refining facilities
shutdown scheduled for Aug. 8 to Sept. 3.  Vodacom Group Ltd. (VOD)  , the largest provider of
mobile-phone services to  South Africans , climbed 1.50 rand, or
1.9 percent, to 80 rand. Headline earnings per share for the 12
months through March are expected to be between 25 percent and
30 percent higher than a year earlier.  To contact the reporters on this story:
